The java virtual machine context.

When you write Java, the compiler turns your source file into bytecode, a portable instruction set. The java virtual machine then loads that bytecode and executes it. So a file called Main dot java compiles into a file called Main dot class, the virtual machine loads that class, it garbage-collects as it runs, and it compiles your hottest code paths down to native machine code on the fly.

Two consequences are worth absorbing right now. The first is that startup is not instant. The virtual machine itself takes a moment to boot up. For a tiny script that can feel slow, but for a long-running service it disappears into the noise.

The second consequence is that you inherit all of the virtual machine's strengths. You get a mature garbage collector, a compiler that actually gets faster the longer your program runs, and decades of battle-tested profiling tools.
